<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ch1-section-finite-differencing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Finite differencing</title>

    <p>
        Rarely do we know the form of the differentiable function that describes a given state variable.
        But thanks to meteorological instruments and numerical and artificial intelligence (AI) weather models,
        we do have discrete measurements of various state variable in space and time,
        and so we can apply <term>finite differencing</term> to approximate derivatives using discrete differences between measurements.
    </p>

    <p>
        Consider the one-dimensional case first.
        If we have measurements of a state variable <m>f(x)</m> at a central point <m>x_0</m>
        and two other points <m>x_1 = x_0 - \Delta x</m> and <m>x_2 = x_0 + \Delta x</m> each spaced <m>\Delta x</m> from the central point,
        as shown in <xref ref="ch1-centered-difference" text="type-global" /> below, we can make the approximations
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-difference-quotient" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{df}{dx} \right|_{x=x_0}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2) - f(x_1)}{2 \Delta x}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-difference-quotient-second" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{d^2f}{dx^2} \right|_{x=x_0}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2) - 2f(x_0) + f(x_1)}{(\Delta x)^2}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Note that <xref ref="eqn-difference-quotient" text="type-global" /> is equivalent to the <term>difference quotient</term> of precalculus.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch1-centered-difference">
        <caption>
            Adapted from Martin Figure 1.6.
            Example of centered differencing.
            Central point <m>x_0</m> and equally-spaced surrounding points <m>x_1 = x_0 - \Delta x</m> and <m>x_2 = x_0 + \Delta x</m>,
            where <m>\Delta x \gt 0 </m> is distance from <m>x_0</m>.
            <m>x</m> increases to the right.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch1-centered-difference.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                A point in the middle of two equally-spaced points.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
        The method of approximating <m>\left. \dfrac{df}{dx} \right|_{x=x_0}</m>
        shown in <xref ref="eqn-difference-quotient" text="type-global" />
        is called <term>centered differencing</term>,
        and its formula comes from subtracting the Taylor Series expansion of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = x_0</m>
        evaluated at <m>x = x_1</m> from the Taylor series expansion of <m>f(x)</m> at <m>x = x_0</m>
        evaluated at <m>x = x_2</m> and then neglecting higher-order terms.
        See <xref ref="martin" text="custom">Martin (2006)</xref> Subsection 1.2.3 for derivations of
        <xref ref="eqn-difference-quotient" text="type-global" />
        and <xref ref="eqn-difference-quotient-second" text="type-global" />.
    </p>

    <p>
        The reasoning of centered differencing can be applied to partial derivatives by only allowing one independent variable to change.
        For example, if we have a state variable <m>f = f(x,y,z,t)</m>,
        we can use centered differencing to approximate its first and second partial derivatives with respect to <m>x</m> as
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-partial-difference-quotient" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \right|_{(x,y,z,t)=(x_0,y_0,z_0,t_0)}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2,y_0,z_0,t_0) - f(x_1,y_0,z_0,t_0)}{2 \Delta x}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-partial-difference-quotient-second" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x^2} \right|_{(x,y,z,t)=(x_0,y_0,z_0,t_0)}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2,y_0,z_0,t_0) - 2 f(x_0,y_0,z_0,t_0) + f(x_1,y_0,z_0,t_0)}{(\Delta x)^2}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        respectively.
    </p>

    <p>
        Furthermore, it is not required that surrounding points be spaced at equal distances around a central point. For example,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-difference-quotient-unbalanced" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{df}{dx} \right|_{x=x_0}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2) - f(x_1)}{x_2 - x_1}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        and
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-partial-difference-quotient-unbalanced" number="yes">
            \left. \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \right|_{(x,y,z,t)=(x_0,y_0,z_0,t_0)}
            \approx
            \frac{f(x_2,y_0,z_0,t_0) - f(x_1,y_0,z_0,t_0)}{x_2 - x_1}  
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        are valid algorithms for approximating ordinary and partial derivatives, respectively,
        including in cases when <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> are not spaced at equal distances from <m>x_0</m>.
        This more general case is shown in <xref ref="ch1-finite-difference" text="type-global" /> below.
        In fact, either <m>x_1</m> or <m>x_2</m> (but not both) could coincide with <m>x_0</m> and these algorithms still would be valid!
    </p>

    <p>
        Once again, <xref ref="eqn-difference-quotient-unbalanced" text="type-global" /> is equivalent to the difference quotient of precalculus.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="ch1-finite-difference">
        <caption>
            Reproduction of <xref ref="ch1-centered-difference" text="type-global" />,
            but the surrounding points <m>x_1</m> and <m>x_2</m> are not equally spaced from the central point <m>x_0</m>.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ch1-finite-difference.png" width="60%">
            <shortdescription>
                A point in the middle of two unequally-spaced points.
            </shortdescription>
        </image>
    </figure>

</section>